<div id="review_73828447" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/73828447" />
    <a title="Brennan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2818198-brennan"><img alt="Brennan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1452426886p2/2818198.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/73828447?book_show_action=true">Oct 07, 2009</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Brennan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Brennan" href="/user/show/2818198-brennan">Brennan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer73828447" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1286330260721612063">In a word: sprawling. This is certainly not a quick read; Guanzhong&apos;s epic contains hundreds of characters, battles, and events that need to be properly stored in memory for the reader to understand the novel. The book is roughly 70% historically accurate, which allows for a mostly-solid basis for the author to expand upon. This is not an unbiased record of the Three Kingdoms Era, as the Shu-Han faction, and Liu Bei in particular, is lionized while Cao Cao&apos;s Wei is often put in a negative light.</span>
  <span id="freeText1286330260721612063" style="display:none">In a word: sprawling. This is certainly not a quick read; Guanzhong's epic contains hundreds of characters, battles, and events that need to be properly stored in memory for the reader to understand the novel. The book is roughly 70% historically accurate, which allows for a mostly-solid basis for the author to expand upon. This is not an unbiased record of the Three Kingdoms Era, as the Shu-Han faction, and Liu Bei in particular, is lionized while Cao Cao's Wei is often put in a negative light. The lack of neutrality may lead readers to view the Three Kingdoms in a black-and-white perspective, but the use of protagonists gives an extremely entertaining read. It's a challenge to keep up with Three Kingdom's details, but in the end, it's well worth doing so.</span>
  <a data-text-id="1286330260721612063" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
