    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4192959674" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4192959674" />
    <a title="saïd" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/27143253-sa-d"><img alt="saïd" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1576544217p2/27143253.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4192959674?book_show_action=true">Dec 19, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="saïd" class="user" itemprop="url" name="saïd" href="/user/show/27143253-sa-d">saïd</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/27143253-sa-d?shelf=traduction-talk">traduction-talk</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/27143253-sa-d?shelf=zh-tw-hk-mn">zh-tw-hk-mn</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/27143253-sa-d?shelf=1_fiction">1_fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4192959674" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6183590943093685826">Reading super old things makes me feel so weird. This epic story was written in the 14th century, isn&apos;t that amazing?<br/><br/>There are three primary translations of <i>Romance of the Three Kingdoms</i> (三国演义) available to English-speakers: Charles Henry Brewitt-Taylor, Moss Roberts, and Martin Palmer. There are quite a few differences between the three extant English-language translations, which is only to be expected, since together they span nearly a century.<blockquote><strong>CHARLES HENRY BREWITT-TAYLOR</strong> (1925)</blockquote>This translatio</span>
  <span id="freeText6183590943093685826" style="display:none">Reading super old things makes me feel so weird. This epic story was written in the 14th century, isn't that amazing?<br /><br />There are three primary translations of <i>Romance of the Three Kingdoms</i> (三国演义) available to English-speakers: Charles Henry Brewitt-Taylor, Moss Roberts, and Martin Palmer. There are quite a few differences between the three extant English-language translations, which is only to be expected, since together they span nearly a century.<blockquote><strong>CHARLES HENRY BREWITT-TAYLOR</strong> (1925)</blockquote>This translation is, of course, out of copyright, and thus the easiest to find digitally if you don't feel like getting (or can't find) a physical copy. Brewitt-Taylor's translation has been reprinted multiple times over the past century, usually as a two-volume set. This version uses the Wade-Giles transliteration system, so names are spelled Ts'ao Ts'ao (Cao Cao), Chu'ko Liang (Zhuge Liang), Sun Chuan (Sun Quan), Ch'en Kong (Chen Gong), etc. Brewitt-Taylor's version reads exactly like a novel—no maps, no notes, no context; nothing. Most reprints also have not been corrected, so there are quite a few errors such as misspellings and suchlike. The prose, however, is beautiful; typically for the 1920s, the language is fluid without being overly florid, and nowadays has a slightly archaic feel that can be suitable, given the time period of the original text's composition. In short, this is the Constance Garnett version.<blockquote><strong>MOSS ROBERTS</strong> (1991)</blockquote>Roberts's translation is by far the most academic, including around 200 pages of notes, as well as several maps and a detailed introductory essay on the text by none other than Roberts himself. This version is available as a two-volume set containing the entire text, or as a single-volume abridged version (omitting several dozen chapters). The romanisation system used is pinyin, thankfully. One detail that made it difficult to read this version at my usual pace was the fact that Roberts tends not to include paragraph breaks where they would be natural in English-language writing (new speaker, new location, new concept, etc.); the original Chinese text similarly does not include as many breaks, resulting in rather long paragraphs full of multiple speakers' lines of dialogue, which can become confusing. Patience and dedication will resolve any complications, however, and I was comforted by the fact that Roberts's translation includes more contextual information than most Chinese-language editions of the original text.<blockquote><strong>MARTIN PALMER</strong> (2018)</blockquote>Also an abridged version, only around 600 pages (for comparison, the edition I read is over 2300 pages), including roughly a third of the total text. Unlike Roberts's abridgement, which removed entire chapters, Palmer's abridgement preserves sections from each chapter, although slimmed down significantly. Thus this version includes the entire story, more or less, but in a rather truncated format, which feels clunky and rushed (which it is). In my opinion there's really no reason to read this version unless you're a masochistic completionist—reading the Wikipedia page for the original text would be a better use of your time, and would probably be more in-depth anyway.<blockquote>
  <strong>CONCLUSION</strong>
</blockquote>Moss Roberts's 1991 translation is by far the most accurate and comprehensive English-language version. Yes, it's incredibly long, but if you're actually looking for a real version of the story (as opposed to Cliff Notes or the like), Roberts's is the best that's currently available.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6183590943093685826" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


